Title: Dracula
Credit: Written by
Author: Bram Stoker
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 7/20/2026
Notes: Period live-action; gothic 1890s Europe. Closed cast; lock looks in Action. Jonathan Harker's journal voice is JONATHAN HARKER V.O. unless he speaks on camera.

===

INT. BRITISH MUSEUM LIBRARY - DAY

Gaslight on high shelves. JONATHAN HARKER, late twenties, neat brown hair, clean-shaven English solicitor in a dark traveling suit, bends over maps and heavy folios. He copies notes into a small shorthand journal with careful, lawyerly hand.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
Having had some time at my disposal when in London, I visited the British Museum and made search among the books and maps regarding Transylvania. The district he named is in the extreme east of the country, just on the borders of three states, in the midst of the Carpathian mountains—one of the wildest and least known portions of Europe. I was not able to light on any map giving the exact locality of the Castle Dracula. Bistritz, the post town named by Count Dracula, is a fairly well-known place.

He underlines a name on the page: BISTRITZ. Closes the journal.

EXT. TRAIN - DANUBE BRIDGE - DAY

A steam train crosses a wide, noble river on a splendid western bridge. Jonathan at the window watches the city fall behind.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
Left Munich at 8:35 P.M. on 1st May, arriving at Vienna early next morning. Buda-Pesth seems a wonderful place. The impression I had was that we were leaving the West and entering the East.

EXT. KLAUSENBURGH STREET - NIGHT

Oil lamps. Narrow old street. Jonathan, valise in hand, finds the painted sign of the HOTEL ROYALE and goes in.

INT. HOTEL ROYALE DINING ROOM - NIGHT

Low-beamed room. Jonathan finishes a reddish chicken dish, drinks water thirstily. A WAITER in an apron clears.

JONATHAN HARKER
Paprika hendl, you called it?

WAITER
National dish. Anywhere along the Carpathians.

Jonathan scribbles in his journal.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
Mem., get recipe for Mina. My smattering of German is very useful here. I don't know how I should get on without it.

INT. HOTEL ROYALE, JONATHAN'S ROOM - NIGHT

A comfortable bed. Outside, a DOG HOWLS under the window without cease. Jonathan twists, thirsty, carafe empty. Queer half-dreams: dark peaks, a flapping shape. Toward morning he sleeps hard—then continuous KNOCKING at the door jolts him awake.

INT. HOTEL ROYALE DINING ROOM - MORNING

Breakfast: more paprika, maize porridge, stuffed eggplant. Jonathan eats in haste, watch open beside the plate.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
Mamaliga—and impletata. Mem., get recipe for this also. I had to hurry. The further east you go the more unpunctual are the trains. What ought they to be in China?

EXT. CARPATHIAN COUNTRYSIDE - DAY

Through the carriage window: little towns and castles on steep hills as in old missals; rivers with wide stony flood-margins; stations crowded with peasants.

Women in full white sleeves and big belts with fluttering strips. SLOVAKS in big cowboy hats, baggy dirty-white trousers, enormous brass-studded leather belts, high boots, long black hair and heavy moustaches—picturesque as stage brigands.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
All day long we seemed to dawdle through a country full of beauty of every kind. In the population of Transylvania there are four distinct nationalities. I am going among the Szekelys, who claim to be descended from Attila and the Huns. Every known superstition in the world is gathered into the horseshoe of the Carpathians, as if it were the centre of some sort of imaginative whirlpool. Mem., I must ask the Count all about them.

EXT. BISTRITZ - TWILIGHT

An interesting old frontier town, storm-marked, under darkening sky. Jonathan walks with bag toward a timbered inn sign: GOLDEN KRONE.

EXT. GOLDEN KRONE HOTEL - TWILIGHT

At the door, LANDLADY ELISABETA—elderly, cheery-looking, white undergarment with long double apron of coloured stuff fitting almost too tight for modesty—bows as Jonathan approaches.

LANDLADY ELISABETA
The Herr Englishman?

JONATHAN HARKER
Yes. Jonathan Harker.

She smiles, turns, and speaks quickly to LANDLORD JOSEF—elderly, white shirt-sleeves—who has followed her out. He goes in and returns at once with a sealed letter. Jonathan breaks it and reads by the doorway lamp.

COUNT DRACULA (V.O.)
My Friend. Welcome to the Carpathians. I am anxiously expecting you. Sleep well to-night. At three to-morrow the diligence will start for Bukovina; a place on it is kept for you. At the Borgo Pass my carriage will await you and will bring you to me. I trust that your journey from London has been a happy one, and that you will enjoy your stay in my beautiful land. Your friend, Dracula.

Jonathan looks up, pleased. Elisabeta and Josef exchange a glance he does not yet read.

INT. GOLDEN KRONE HOTEL, JONATHAN'S ROOM - NIGHT

Simple old-fashioned chamber. Jonathan unpacks, sets journal on the table—only his English things. He sleeps uneasily.

INT. GOLDEN KRONE HOTEL, LOBBY - DAY

Morning of 4 May. Jonathan at the desk with Josef. Elisabeta hovers.

JONATHAN HARKER
The Count directed you to secure the best place on the coach?

LANDLORD JOSEF
(mumbling)
The money was sent in a letter. That is all I know.

JONATHAN HARKER
Do you know Count Dracula? Can you tell me anything of his castle?

Josef and Elisabeta cross themselves. Fear tightens both faces.

LANDLORD JOSEF
We know nothing at all.

They refuse to speak further. Josef pretends not to understand Jonathan's German—though a moment before he answered every word.

INT. GOLDEN KRONE HOTEL, JONATHAN'S ROOM - DAY

Just before departure. Elisabeta bursts in, hysterical, German breaking into another tongue.

LANDLADY ELISABETA
Must you go? Oh! young Herr, must you go?

JONATHAN HARKER
I must go at once. I am engaged on important business.

LANDLADY ELISABETA
Do you know what day it is?

JONATHAN HARKER
It is the fourth of May.

LANDLADY ELISABETA
Oh, yes! I know that! I know that, but do you know what day it is? It is the eve of St. George's Day. Do you not know that to-night, when the clock strikes midnight, all the evil things in the world will have full sway? Do you know where you are going, and what you are going to?

She drops to her knees, imploring. Jonathan tries to raise her.

JONATHAN HARKER
I thank you. My duty is imperative, and I must go.

She rises, dries her eyes, takes a crucifix from her neck, offers it. Jonathan hesitates—English Churchman, uneasy at the idolatrous look of it. She sees the doubt and puts the rosary round his neck herself.

LANDLADY ELISABETA
For your mother's sake.

She goes out. Jonathan stands alone, the crucifix on his breast. Coach horn distant below.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
I am writing up this part of the diary whilst I am waiting for the coach, which is, of course, late; and the crucifix is still round my neck. Whether it is the old lady's fear, or the many ghostly traditions of this place, or the crucifix itself, I do not know, but I am not feeling nearly as easy in my mind as usual. If this book should ever reach Mina before I do, let it bring my good-bye. Here comes the coach!

EXT. GOLDEN KRONE HOTEL YARD - DAY

Crowd swollen round the wide archway: oleander and orange trees in green tubs. DILIGENCE DRIVER in wide linen drawers on the box of a four-horse coach. Jonathan's luggage goes up.

The Driver talks low with Elisabeta; both look at Jonathan. Peasants on the bench listen, then regard him pityingly. Queer words pass: "Ordog"—Satan; "pokol"—hell; "stregoica"—witch; "vrolok" and "vlkoslak"—were-wolf or vampire.

As the coach starts, people crowd round and cross themselves. A peasant woman puts a crucifix to her lips and points it toward him. Jonathan settles among the passengers, the rosary cold against his skin.

EXT. BORGO PASS ROAD - DUSK

The diligence climbs into wilder country. Dark pines. Jagged rocks. Snow still in the hollows. The sun sinks in a blaze of red. Passengers grow silent.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
I shall never forget the last glimpse which I had of the inn yard and its crowd of picturesque figures, all crossing themselves. By the roadside were many crosses, and as we swept by, our driver and passengers crossed themselves. It grew cold.

EXT. BORGO PASS - NIGHT

Moonlight on the pass. The diligence slows. From the darkness a CALÈCHE drawn by four black horses sweeps up. The DRIVER—tall, wrapped to the eyes in a great black cloak and hat—stands waiting.

DILIGENCE DRIVER
(uneasy)
The English Herr is for Castle Dracula?

The cloaked Driver bows and takes Jonathan's traps. Jonathan climbs into the calèche. The horses leap forward into the night. Behind, the diligence turns and flees.

EXT. FOREST ROAD NEAR CASTLE - NIGHT

The calèche tears through blue-black forest. Wolves howl on every side—blue flames flicker among the trees. Jonathan grips the seat. The Driver raises a hand; the howling falls to silence. Horses race on.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
I was afraid to speak or move. The time seemed interminable. Suddenly I became conscious of the fact that the driver was in the act of pulling up the horses in the courtyard of a vast ruined castle.

EXT. CASTLE DRACULA COURTYARD - NIGHT

The calèche stands in the gloom of a vast ruined courtyard. Dark ways lead off under great round arches. Tall black windows give no light. Broken battlements cut a jagged line against the moonlit sky.

The DRIVER—tall, wrapped, face still unseen—jumps down and holds out his hand. Jonathan takes it. The grip is a steel vice; prodigious strength. Jonathan winces.

The Driver sets Jonathan's traps on the ground beside a great door: old, studded with large iron nails, set in a projecting doorway of massive stone. Even in dim light the carving shows, worn by time and weather.

The Driver springs back into his seat, shakes the reins. Horses start. Trap and all disappear down one of the dark openings.

Jonathan stands alone before the door. No bell. No knocker. Frowning walls. Dark window openings.

He waits. Doubts and fears crowd him. He rubs his eyes, pinches his own flesh. Awake. Among the Carpathians.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
What sort of place have I come to, and among what kind of people? Solicitor's clerk—Mina would not like that. Solicitor—for I am now a full-blown solicitor. It all seems like a horrible nightmare.

A heavy step behind the great door. Through the chinks: the gleam of a coming light.

Rattling chains. Clanking of massive bolts drawn back. A key turns with the loud grating of long disuse.

The great door swings back.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA ENTRANCE HALL - NIGHT

Within stands COUNT DRACULA: tall old man, clean-shaven save a long white moustache, clad in black from head to foot without a single speck of colour. In his hand an antique silver lamp, flame burning without chimney or globe, throwing long quivering shadows in the draught.

He motions Jonathan in with a courtly gesture of the right hand. Excellent English; strange intonation. He does not step to meet him—stands like a statue, fixed by his own welcome.

COUNT DRACULA
Welcome to my house! Enter freely and of your own will!

Jonathan steps over the threshold.

The Count moves impulsively forward, grasps Jonathan's hand. Strength that makes him wince. Cold as ice—more like the hand of a dead than a living man.

COUNT DRACULA
Welcome to my house. Come freely. Go safely; and leave something of the happiness you bring!

The handshake so akin to the Driver's that Jonathan stares.

JONATHAN HARKER
Count Dracula?

The Count bows in a courtly way.

COUNT DRACULA
I am Dracula; and I bid you welcome, Mr. Harker, to my house. Come in; the night air is chill, and you must need to eat and rest.

He sets the lamp on a wall bracket, steps out, takes Jonathan's luggage before Jonathan can forestall him. Jonathan protests. The Count insists.

COUNT DRACULA
Nay, sir, you are my guest. It is late, and my people are not available. Let me see to your comfort myself.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA PASSAGE AND STAIR - NIGHT

The Count carries the traps along a stone passage, then up a great winding stair. Another great passage—steps ring heavily on stone.

At the end he throws open a heavy door.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA DINING ROOM - NIGHT

A well-lit room. A table spread for supper. On the mighty hearth a great fire of logs, freshly replenished, flames and flares.

The Count sets down the bags, closes the door, crosses, opens another door.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA OCTAGONAL ROOM - NIGHT

A small octagonal room lit by a single lamp. Seemingly without a window. The Count opens a further door and motions Jonathan through.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA BEDROOM - NIGHT

A great bedroom, well lighted and warmed with another log fire—top logs fresh—sending a hollow roar up the wide chimney.

The Count leaves the luggage inside and withdraws at the door.

COUNT DRACULA
You will need, after your journey, to refresh yourself by making your toilet. I trust you will find all you wish. When you are ready, come into the other room, where you will find your supper prepared.

The door closes.

Light, warmth, courteous welcome. Jonathan's doubts ease. He is half famished. Hasty toilet—then he goes.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA DINING ROOM - NIGHT

Supper laid out. Count Dracula stands to one side of the great fireplace, leaning against the stonework. A graceful wave of the hand to the table.

COUNT DRACULA
I pray you, be seated and sup how you please. You will, I trust, excuse me that I do not join you; but I have dined already, and I do not sup.

Jonathan hands him a sealed letter. The Count opens it, reads gravely, then with a charming smile hands it back. Jonathan's eye catches a passage; pleasure.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
"He is a young man, full of energy and talent... discreet and silent... He shall be ready to attend on you when you will during his stay..."

The Count takes the cover from a dish. Excellent roast chicken, cheese, salad, a bottle of old Tokay. Jonathan eats. Two glasses of wine.

During the meal the Count asks many questions as to the journey. Jonathan tells him, by degrees, all he has experienced.

Supper done. At the Count's desire Jonathan draws a chair by the fire and smokes a cigar the Count offers—excusing himself that he does not smoke.

Firelight on the Count. Jonathan observes him.

Strong—very strong—aquiline face; high bridge of the thin nose; peculiarly arched nostrils; lofty domed forehead; hair scant round the temples but profuse elsewhere. Eyebrows massive, almost meeting over the nose, bushy hair curling in its own profusion. Mouth under the heavy moustache fixed and rather cruel-looking; peculiarly sharp white teeth protruding over the lips; remarkable ruddiness of those lips. Ears pale, extremely pointed at the tops. Chin broad and strong; cheeks firm though thin. Extraordinary pallor.

The backs of the hands on his knees seemed white and fine—close now: coarse, broad, squat fingers. Hairs in the centre of the palm. Nails long and fine, cut to a sharp point.

The Count leans over; his hands touch Jonathan. Jonathan cannot repress a shudder. Rank breath—horrible nausea he cannot conceal.

The Count notices, draws back. A grim sort of smile shows more than yet his protuberant teeth. He sits again on his own side of the fireplace.

Silence. Jonathan looks toward the window: the first dim streak of coming dawn. Strange stillness—then, from down below in the valley, the howling of many wolves.

The Count's eyes gleam.

COUNT DRACULA
Listen to them—the children of the night. What music they make!

He reads something in Jonathan's face.

COUNT DRACULA
Ah, sir, you dwellers in the city cannot enter into the feelings of the hunter.

He rises.

COUNT DRACULA
But you must be tired. Your bedroom is all ready, and to-morrow you shall sleep as late as you will. I have to be away till the afternoon; so sleep well and dream well!

A courteous bow. He opens the door to the octagonal room himself. Jonathan enters toward the bedroom.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA BEDROOM - NIGHT

Jonathan alone. The fire sinks. He sits with his journal.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
I am all in a sea of wonders. I doubt; I fear; I think strange things, which I dare not confess to my own soul. God keep me, if only for the sake of those dear to me!

INT. CASTLE DRACULA DINING ROOM - DAY

Early morning light—7 May. Jonathan enters dressed. A cold breakfast laid out; coffee kept hot on the hearth.

A card on the table.

INSERT - THE CARD
I have to be absent for a while. Do not wait for me.—D.

He eats a hearty meal. Looks for a bell to signal servants—finds none.

Gold table service, beautifully wrought. Costliest curtains, upholstery, hangings. Yet nowhere a looking-glass. Jonathan shaves by touch at a small travelling glass from his bag.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA LIBRARY - DAY

A vast room of books—English, French, and more. Jonathan explores shelves: history, politics, geography, blue books, the Law List, army and navy lists, Whitaker's Almanack, the London Directory. He settles to read of England.

Later the Count returns, delighted to find him among the volumes.

COUNT DRACULA
These friends have been good friends to me. Through them I have walked London's streets and learned her life. But a man cannot live on books alone. I would know your English tongue and English ways more perfectly. You shall tell me of your London.

They talk long. The Count's hunger for detail is endless—houses, customs, law.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA LIBRARY - NIGHT

Night after night. Business of the London purchase: Carfax, an old house near Purfleet, chapel and all. Jonathan explains deeds, settlements, the need for local agents.

COUNT DRACULA
I am glad that it is old and big. I myself am of an old family, and to live in a new house would kill me. A house cannot be made habitable in a day; and, after all, how few days go to make up a century.

Jonathan draws papers. The Count signs with a hand that never warms.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA BEDROOM - DAY

Jonathan rises and goes to shave. His travelling mirror on the window ledge. He hears the Count behind him—yet in the glass, no reflection but his own.

A hand falls on his shoulder. Jonathan starts. The razor nicks his chin. Blood wells.

The Count's eyes blaze at the red drop. His hand snatches toward Jonathan's throat—then recoils from the crucifix on the chain. The fury dies to a cold smile.

COUNT DRACULA
Take care how you cut yourself. It is more dangerous than you think in this country.

He takes the mirror.

COUNT DRACULA
This is a foul bauble of man's vanity. Away with it!

He flings it out the window. Glass shatters far below on the stones.

Jonathan stands shaken, blood on his collar, the empty air where a reflection should have been.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA STAIRS AND SOUTH ROOM - DAY

Jonathan rushes the corridors like a rat in a trap—up the stairs, down again, wrenching every door, peering from every window. Locked. Bolted. Locked.

He stops. The wildness drains out of him. He sits down quietly on the cold stone—quieter than he has ever done anything in his life—and thinks.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
Of one thing only am I certain; that it is no use making my ideas known to the Count. He knows well that I am imprisoned. My only plan will be to keep my knowledge and my fears to myself, and my eyes open.

Below—the great door shuts. The Count has returned.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA BEDROOM - DAY

Jonathan goes cautiously to his own room. Through the doorway he sees COUNT DRACULA making the bed—smoothing the coverlet with those pale, long-nailed hands.

Jonathan draws back, shaken.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
This was odd, but only confirmed what I had all along thought—that there were no servants in the house.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA DINING ROOM - DAY

Through the chink of the hinges Jonathan watches the Count lay the table himself—plates, covers, the careful placement of each piece.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
If he does himself all these menial offices, surely it is proof that there is no one else to do them. Then it must have been the Count himself who was the driver of the coach that brought me here. What does it mean that he could control the wolves by only holding up his hand in silence?

INT. CASTLE DRACULA BEDROOM - DAY

Jonathan alone. He touches the crucifix at his throat—holds it hard.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
Bless that good, good woman who hung the crucifix round my neck! For it is a comfort and a strength to me whenever I touch it. To-night he may talk of himself, if I turn the conversation that way. I must be very careful not to awake his suspicion.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA LIBRARY - NIGHT

Firelight. Midnight. Jonathan and the Count. Maps and old volumes about them. Jonathan has steered the talk to Transylvania history. The Count warms to it—walks the room, pulling his great white moustache, grasping whatever his hands find as though he would crush it.

COUNT DRACULA
We Szekelys have a right to be proud, for in our veins flows the blood of many brave races who fought as the lion fights, for lordship. Here, in the whirlpool of European races, the Ugric tribe bore down from Iceland the fighting spirit which Thor and Wodin gave them, which their Berserkers displayed to such fell intent on the seaboards of Europe, ay, and of Asia and Africa too, till the peoples thought that the were-wolves themselves had come.

He holds up his arms.

COUNT DRACULA
Here, too, when they came, they found the Huns, whose warlike fury had swept the earth like a living flame. Fools, fools! What devil or what witch was ever so great as Attila, whose blood is in these veins? Is it a wonder that we were a conquering race?

He paces—voice rising, eyes bright.

COUNT DRACULA
Who more gladly than we throughout the Four Nations received the "bloody sword," or at its warlike call flocked quicker to the standard of the King? When was redeemed that great shame of my nation, the shame of Cassova, when the flags of the Wallach and the Magyar went down beneath the Crescent? Who was it but one of my own race who as Voivode crossed the Danube and beat the Turk on his own ground? This was a Dracula indeed!

Jonathan listens, fascinated and cold.

COUNT DRACULA
Woe was it that his own unworthy brother, when he had fallen, sold his people to the Turk and brought the shame of slavery on them! Was it not this Dracula, indeed, who inspired that other of his race who in a later age again and again brought his forces over the great river into Turkey-land; who, when he was beaten back, came again, and again, and again, though he had to come alone from the bloody field where his troops were being slaughtered, since he knew that he alone could ultimately triumph!

The Count's hands close on the back of a chair until the wood complains.

COUNT DRACULA
They said that he thought only of himself. Bah! What good are peasants without a leader? Ah, young sir, the Szekelys—and the Dracula as their heart's blood, their brains, and their swords—can boast a record that mushroom growths like the Hapsburgs and the Romanoffs can never reach. The warlike days are over. Blood is too precious a thing in these days of dishonourable peace; and the glories of the great races are as a tale that is told.

Close on morning. They go to bed.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
This diary seems horribly like the beginning of the Arabian Nights, for everything has to break off at cockcrow—or like the ghost of Hamlet's father.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA LIBRARY - NIGHT

Another night. Books open. The Count questions Jonathan on legal matters—methodical, precise.

COUNT DRACULA
Might a man in England have two solicitors or more?

JONATHAN HARKER
He might have a dozen if he wished. But it would not be wise to have more than one solicitor engaged in one transaction.

COUNT DRACULA
I shall illustrate. Your friend and mine, Mr. Peter Hawkins, from under the shadow of your beautiful cathedral at Exeter, buys for me through your good self my place at London. Good! My motive was that no local interest might be served save my wish only. Now, suppose I, who have much of affairs, wish to ship goods, say, to Newcastle, or Durham, or Harwich, or Dover—might it not be that it could with more ease be done by consigning to one in these ports?

JONATHAN HARKER
Certainly it would be most easy. We solicitors have a system of agency one for the other, so that local work could be done locally on instruction.

COUNT DRACULA
But I could be at liberty to direct myself. Is it not so?

JONATHAN HARKER
Of course. Such is often done by men of business, who do not like the whole of their affairs to be known by any one person.

COUNT DRACULA
Good!

He presses on—consignments, forms, difficulties guarded against by forethought. Jonathan answers from the books. The Count misses nothing.

Then the Count stands.

COUNT DRACULA
Have you written since your first letter to our friend Mr. Peter Hawkins, or to any other?

JONATHAN HARKER
I have not. As yet I have not seen any opportunity of sending letters to anybody.

The Count lays a heavy hand on Jonathan's shoulder.

COUNT DRACULA
Then write now, my young friend. Write to our friend and to any other; and say, if it will please you, that you shall stay with me until a month from now.

JONATHAN HARKER
Do you wish me to stay so long?

COUNT DRACULA
I desire it much; nay, I will take no refusal. When your master engaged that someone should come on his behalf, it was understood that my needs only were to be consulted. I have not stinted. Is it not so?

Jonathan bows acceptance. His face shows the trouble. The Count sees the victory.

COUNT DRACULA
I pray you, my good young friend, that you will not discourse of things other than business in your letters. It will doubtless please your friends to know that you are well, and that you look forward to getting home to them. Is it not so?

He hands Jonathan three sheets of the thinnest foreign post and three envelopes. The quiet smile—sharp canine teeth over the red underlip. Jonathan understands: the Count will read what he writes.

Jonathan writes two formal notes. The Count writes several of his own, referring to books on the table. He gathers Jonathan's letters with his, sets writing materials aside, and leaves.

The door closes. Jonathan is alone—prisoner in all but name.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA SOUTH ROOM - NIGHT

Jonathan, restless, finds a door unlocked that was not before. He enters a dusty chamber long unused—old furniture, moth-eaten hangings, a great bed. Moonlight through tall windows.

He lies down in his clothes, exhausted, the crucifix at his throat.

Sleep takes him—then half-waking horror.

Three young women materialize in the moonlight. Two dark, with hard bright pride and full red lips; one fair, with golden hair and eyes like pale sapphires—all voluptuous, all with brilliant white teeth that shine like pearls against the ruby of their voluptuous lips.

They whisper together. A silvery, musical laugh.

FAIR WOMAN
Go on! You are first, and we shall follow; yours is the right to begin.

DARK WOMAN
He is young and strong; there are kisses for us all.

Jonathan cannot move. The fair woman advances, licks her lips like an animal. She bends over him. He feels the soft shiver of her breath—then the sharp points of teeth upon his throat—

A howl of fury. COUNT DRACULA stands in the room, eyes flaming red, the women recoiling.

COUNT DRACULA
How dare you touch him, any of you? How dare you cast eyes on him when I had forbidden it? Back, I tell you all! This man belongs to me! Beware how you meddle with him, or you'll have to deal with me.

FAIR WOMAN
(hard, mocking)
You yourself never loved; you never love!

The Count flings her aside. From a bag he carries he tosses them a sack—something small writhes within. They seize it with greedy joy and vanish through the moonlight like mist.

COUNT DRACULA
(to Jonathan, almost gently)
To-morrow, my friend, we must conclude our business. Tomorrow you sleep as usual in your own room.

Darkness. Jonathan knows no more.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA JONATHAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

Morning light. JONATHAN HARKER jolts awake in his own bed—clothes folded beside him in a manner not his habit. His watch lies unwound.

He checks his pockets: intact. He clutches his diary, relief flooding his face.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
If the Count carried me here and undressed me, he must have been hurried. This diary would have been a mystery he would not have brooked. As I look round this room, it is now a sort of sanctuary—for nothing can be more dreadful than those awful women, who were—who are—waiting to suck my blood.

He rises, pale, and forces himself toward the door.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA STAIRS AND SOUTH ROOM - DAY

Jonathan climbs to the doorway at the top of the stairs. The door is closed—forcibly driven against the jamb, woodwork splintered. The bolt of the lock has not been shot, yet the door is fastened from the inside.

He presses his palm to the splintered wood. Listens. Nothing.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
I fear it was no dream, and must act on this surmise. I am surely in the toils.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA LIBRARY - NIGHT

Candlelight. COUNT DRACULA sits opposite Jonathan, suave, eyes never leaving him. Writing paper, ink, and three clean sheets lie between them.

COUNT DRACULA
I would have you write three letters, my friend. One saying that your work here is nearly done, and that you should start for home within a few days. Another that you are starting on the next morning from the time of the letter. And the third—that you have left the castle and arrived at Bistritz.

Jonathan's hand tightens on the pen. He glances at the Count's eyes—something of that gathering wrath he saw when the fair woman was hurled aside.

COUNT DRACULA
Posts are few and uncertain. Your writing now will ensure ease of mind to your friends. I shall countermand the later letters, which would be held over at Bistritz until due time—in case chance would admit of your prolonging your stay.

JONATHAN HARKER
(forced calm)
What dates should I put on the letters?

The Count calculates a moment.

COUNT DRACULA
The first should be June 12, the second June 19, and the third June 29.

Jonathan writes. His face goes bloodless.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
I know now the span of my life. God help me!

EXT. CASTLE DRACULA COURTYARD - DAY

A band of SZGANY—gipsies in rough coats and wide hats—encamp in the courtyard. Smoke from small fires. Horses tethered. They move with easy fearlessness, speaking Romany among themselves.

At a barred upper window, Jonathan appears. He calls down, waving. The Szgany take off their hats, make obeisance and many signs he cannot understand.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
There is a chance of escape—or at any rate of being able to send word home. These Szgany are almost outside all law. I shall write some letters home, and try to get them posted.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA JONATHAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

Jonathan finishes two letters at a small table. One in ordinary hand; one in shorthand.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
Mina's is in shorthand, and I simply ask Mr. Hawkins to communicate with her. To her I have explained my situation—but without the horrors. It would shock and frighten her to death were I to expose my heart.

He folds them, adds a gold piece, and goes to the barred window.

EXT. CASTLE DRACULA COURTYARD - DAY

Jonathan throws the letters and the gold through the bars. A SZGANY MAN catches them, presses them to his heart, bows, and tucks them into his cap.

Jonathan makes urgent signs: post them. The man nods and turns away among his fellows.

Jonathan draws back from the window.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA LIBRARY - DAY

Jonathan reads by the window. The door opens. Count Dracula enters, smoothest voice, two letters in his hand. He sits beside Jonathan.

COUNT DRACULA
The Szgany has given me these, of which, though I know not whence they come, I shall, of course, take care. See!—one is from you, and to my friend Peter Hawkins; the other—

He opens the shorthand letter. Strange symbols. The dark look comes into his face. His eyes blaze wickedly.

COUNT DRACULA
—the other is a vile thing, an outrage upon friendship and hospitality! It is not signed. Well! so it cannot matter to us.

He holds letter and envelope in the flame of the lamp until they are consumed. Ash drifts.

COUNT DRACULA
The letter to Hawkins—that I shall, of course, send on, since it is yours. Your letters are sacred to me. Your pardon, my friend, that unknowingly I did break the seal. Will you not cover it again?

He holds out the Hawkins letter and, with a courteous bow, a clean envelope. Jonathan redirects it in silence and hands it back.

The Count goes out. Soft turn of a key. Jonathan crosses to the door—locked.

Hours later. Jonathan sleeps on the sofa. The Count re-enters, courteous, cheery.

COUNT DRACULA
So, my friend, you are tired? Get to bed. There is the surest rest. I may not have the pleasure to talk to-night, since there are many labours to me; but you will sleep, I pray.

Jonathan rises and goes.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA JONATHAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Jonathan lies down. Exhaustion takes him. No dreams.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
Despair has its own calms.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA JONATHAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

Morning. Jonathan opens his bag for paper and envelopes—every scrap gone. Notes, memoranda of railways and travel, letter of credit: vanished.

He searches the portmanteau and wardrobe. The suit in which he travelled—gone. Overcoat. Rug. No trace.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
This looked like some new scheme of villainy.

EXT. CASTLE DRACULA COURTYARD - DAY

Cracking of whips. Pounding and scraping of horses' feet up the rocky path. Two great leiter-wagons, each drawn by eight sturdy horses, drive into the yard. At the head of each pair, a SLOVAK—wide hat, nail-studded belt, dirty sheepskin, high boots, long stave in hand.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA JONATHAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

Jonathan runs to his door—fastened on the outside. He rushes to the window and cries out.

EXT. CASTLE DRACULA COURTYARD - DAY

The Slovaks look up stupidly and point. The HETMAN of the Szgany steps out, sees them pointing to Jonathan's window, speaks. The Slovaks laugh. Thereafter they resolutely turn away—no piteous cry moves them.

They unload great square boxes with thick rope handles—empty by the ease of handling and their resonance. The boxes stack in a heap in one corner of the yard. The Szgany pay the Slovaks; the men spit on the coins for luck and take their horses. Whips crack. The wagons die away into the distance.

Jonathan's face at the bars, helpless.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA SOUTH ROOM - NIGHT

Before morning. Jonathan has run up the winding stair. He watches from the south window.

Below and across: from the Count's window, a figure emerges—the whole man. COUNT DRACULA wears Jonathan's travelling suit, the terrible bag slung over his shoulder. He crawls down the wall, lizard-fashion, head down, and is gone into the dark.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
There could be no doubt as to his quest, and in my garb, too! He will allow others to see me, as they think—so that any wickedness which he may do shall by the local people be attributed to me.

Jonathan sits doggedly at the window. Moonlight. Quaint little specks float in the rays—tiniest grains of dust, whirling, gathering in clusters.

A low, piteous howling of dogs far below in the valley. The motes dance faster. Moonbeams quiver. Dim phantom shapes gather from the light—the three women again, materializing from the dust.

Jonathan starts broad awake—and runs screaming from the place.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA CHAPEL CRYPT - DAY

Jonathan, desperate, finds a way down through ruined passages into a chapel vault. Earth floor. Old tombs. The great square boxes from the courtyard, now filled with earth—fifty of them.

In one open box, COUNT DRACULA lies—not dead, not sleeping as men sleep. Eyes open, stony. Gorged with blood until his cheeks are swollen and dark, lips crimson, a horrible smirk of satisfaction. The white hair and moustache are dark iron-grey; the face younger, crueler.

Jonathan seizes a shovel. Raises it to strike—

The eyes seem to look at him. The smirk deepens. Courage fails. The shovel drops.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
A terrible desire came upon me to rid the world of such a monster. There was no lethal weapon at hand, but I seized a shovel... And then the eye saw me. I fled.

He staggers back up into the light, broken.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA JONATHAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Last night. The boxes are gone from the yard—loaded for the journey. Jonathan hears the Szgany below. He writes a final entry, hand shaking.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
I shall not remain alone with them. I shall try to scale the wall. At least God's mercy is better than that of these monsters, and the precipice is steep and high. At its foot a man may sleep—as a man. Good-bye, Mina, if I fail; good-bye, all. God help me!

He knots sheets, climbs to the window ledge, and lowers himself into the abyss of night.

FADE TO BLACK.

INT. MINA MURRAY'S LODGINGS - NIGHT

Gaslight. A neat, modest room. MINA MURRAY, mid-twenties, dark hair simply dressed, plain practical gown, sits at a small desk crowded with exercise books, a shorthand manual, and a typewriter.

She practices stenography with fierce concentration, then feeds a sheet into the machine and types a clean line. A school bell's echo seems to linger in her posture—tired, determined.

She takes up a pen and writes a letter, speaking half under her breath as the words form.

MINA MURRAY
My dearest Lucy— Forgive my long delay in writing, but I have been simply overwhelmed with work. The life of an assistant schoolmistress is sometimes trying.

She glances at a small photograph of JONATHAN HARKER on the mantel—young, earnest, dark-haired.

MINA MURRAY
I am longing to be with you, and by the sea, where we can talk together freely and build our castles in the air. I have been working very hard lately, because I want to keep up with Jonathan's studies, and I have been practising shorthand very assiduously.

She flexes cramped fingers, smiles at the thought.

MINA MURRAY
When we are married I shall be able to be useful to Jonathan, and if I can stenograph well enough I can take down what he wants to say and write it out for him on the typewriter. He and I sometimes write letters in shorthand, and he is keeping a stenographic journal of his travels abroad.

She unfolds a brief, hurried note—Jonathan's hand—and holds it to the light.

MINA MURRAY
I have just had a few hurried lines from Jonathan from Transylvania. He is well, and will be returning in about a week. I am longing to hear all his news. It must be so nice to see strange countries. I wonder if we—I mean Jonathan and I—shall ever see them together.

A distant clock strikes ten. She starts, sanding the letter.

MINA MURRAY
There is the ten o'clock bell ringing. Good-bye. Your loving Mina.

She adds a quick postscript, eyes bright with mischief.

MINA MURRAY
Tell me all the news when you write. You have not told me anything for a long time. I hear rumours, and especially of a tall, handsome, curly-haired man?

INT. WESTENRA DRAWING ROOM - DAY

A comfortable London house, light through lace curtains. LUCY WESTENRA, nineteen, fair, golden hair in soft curls, pretty summer dress, sits with a letter from Mina open in her lap. MRS. WESTENRA, gentle, middle-aged, embroidering nearby.

ARTHUR HOLMWOOD enters—tall, handsome, curly-haired, well-cut coat, easy breeding. He greets Mrs. Westenra with warm familiarity; she brightens at once.

MRS. WESTENRA
Arthur. How good of you.

ARTHUR HOLMWOOD
Mrs. Westenra. Lucy.

LUCY WESTENRA
(smiling, a little colour)
Mr. Holmwood.

They talk easily—picture-galleries, rides in the park. Arthur's eyes return to Lucy whenever she looks away.

DR. JOHN SEWARD is shown in: twenty-nine, strong jaw, good forehead, dark serious eyes, professional dark suit. He carries his silk hat a shade too carefully. Arthur makes the introduction.

ARTHUR HOLMWOOD
Lucy—Mrs. Westenra—may I present Dr. John Seward.

DR. JOHN SEWARD
(bows; looks Lucy straight in the face as if to read her thoughts)
Miss Westenra. A pleasure.

Lucy meets that gaze, amused and unshaken, then glances toward a pier-glass as if testing her own face against his scrutiny.

LUCY WESTENRA
(lightly, aside to herself)
A tough nut to crack.

Seward almost sits upon his silk hat, catches himself, and thereafter turns a lancet absently between his fingers until Lucy's eyes flick to it with a suppressed start.

INT. WESTENRA DRAWING ROOM - DAY

Later afternoon light. Lucy alone at a writing desk, pen racing, cheeks flushed. She writes as if confiding across a firelit bedroom.

LUCY WESTENRA
My dearest Mina— I must say you tax me very unfairly with being a bad correspondent. I wrote to you twice since we parted, and your last letter was only your second.

She bites the pen, then plunges on.

LUCY WESTENRA
As to the tall, curly-haired man, I suppose it was the one who was with me at the last Pop. That was Mr. Holmwood. He often comes to see us, and he and mamma get on very well together.

A soft smile.

LUCY WESTENRA
We met some time ago a man that would just do for you, if you were not already engaged to Jonathan. He is an excellent parti—handsome, well off, and of good birth. He is a doctor and really clever. Just fancy! He is only nine-and-twenty, and he has an immense lunatic asylum all under his own care.

She sets the pen down, presses both hands to her burning face.

LUCY WESTENRA
There, it is all out. Mina, we have told all our secrets to each other since we were children. Oh, Mina, couldn't you guess? I love him. I am blushing as I write, for although I think he loves me, he has not told me so in words. But oh, Mina, I love him; I love him; I love him!

She laughs through sudden tears, seals the letter in haste.

LUCY WESTENRA
P.S.—I need not tell you this is a secret. Good-night again.

INT. WESTENRA DRAWING ROOM - DAY

May light. The same room, flowers fresh. Lucy in a light gown, restless with happiness and dread.

DR. JOHN SEWARD is shown in just before lunch. Outwardly cool; hands betray him. He sets down his silk hat with exaggerated care, then finds the lancet again and turns it until Lucy nearly flinches.

DR. JOHN SEWARD
Miss Lucy—I must speak straightforwardly. You are very dear to me, though I have known you so little. What my life would be with you to help and cheer me—

He sees tears start in her eyes and breaks off, stricken.

DR. JOHN SEWARD
I am a brute. I will not add to your present trouble. Could you—in time—love me?

Lucy slowly shakes her head. His hands tremble.

DR. JOHN SEWARD
(hesitant, gentle)
I do not want to wring your confidence from you—only to know. If a woman's heart was free, a man might have hope. Do you care already for any one else?

LUCY WESTENRA
(soft, dutiful)
There is some one.

Seward stands. Strong. Grave. He takes both her hands.

DR. JOHN SEWARD
I hope you will be happy. And if you ever wanted a friend, you must count me one of your best.

He bows and goes. Lucy sinks onto the sofa, crying quietly, letter-paper already blotted beside her.

LUCY WESTENRA (V.O.)
Being proposed to is all very nice—but it isn't at all a happy thing when you have to see a poor fellow, whom you know loves you honestly, going away and looking all broken-hearted.

INT. WESTENRA DRAWING ROOM - DAY

After lunch. Sun warmer. QUINCEY MORRIS is alone with Lucy—American, young-looking and fresh-faced, open air burned into his colour, excellent manners under a ready smile. He sits beside her, jolly on the surface, nervous underneath. He takes her hand.

QUINCEY MORRIS
Miss Lucy, I know I ain't good enough to regulate the fixin's of your little shoes, but I guess if you wait till you find a man that is you will go join them seven young women with the lamps when you quit. Won't you just hitch up alongside of me and let us go down the long road together, driving in double harness?

Lucy tries lightness; her voice catches.

LUCY WESTENRA
I do not know anything of hitching. I wasn't broken to harness at all yet.

Quincey's smile fades into seriousness.

QUINCEY MORRIS
I spoke in a light manner. If I made a mistake on so grave, so momentous an occasion for me, I hope you will forgive me.

He pours out earnest love—heart and soul—then checks himself at something in her face. Manly fervour, quiet.

QUINCEY MORRIS
Lucy, you are an honest-hearted girl, I know. I should not be here speaking to you at all, if I did not believe you clean grit, right through to the very depths of your soul. Tell me, like one good fellow to another, is there any one else that you care for? And if there is I'll never trouble you a hair's breadth again, but will be, if you will let me, a very faithful friend.

Lucy's eyes fill. She nods.

LUCY WESTENRA
There is some one I love, though he has not told me yet that he even loves me.

Quincey rises, presses her hand, smiles through hurt.

QUINCEY MORRIS
That's all right. I don't take back a word I said about being proud to be your friend. And, little girl, tell him for me—he won't have an easy task, for I shall stand by and see fair play.

He goes. Lucy weeps—three true hearts, and only one she can take.

INT. WESTENRA DRAWING ROOM - EVENING

Arthur alone with Lucy. No speech at first—only the look between them. He takes her hands.

ARTHUR HOLMWOOD
Lucy—my dear—can you love me?

She answers with her whole face. He draws her close. Outside, evening settles on the quiet street.

LUCY WESTENRA (V.O.)
Oh, Mina, I cannot tell you how truly good and strong and noble he is. He says he wants to tell me all about himself and his people, and that when I know them I shall love them as he does. I am the happiest woman in all the wide world.

INT. SEWARD'S STUDY, PURFLEET ASYLUM - NIGHT

DR. JOHN SEWARD at his phonograph, speaking into the tube—professional mask cracked by private pain.

DR. JOHN SEWARD
I love her with all my heart. I could not, however, speak of my troubles to her. I must work. Work! Work!

He turns to case notes: R. M. RENFIELD, aet. 59—zoophagous maniac; flies, spiders, birds; a theory of life devouring life.

INT. WHITBY STATION PLATFORM - DAY

MINA MURRAY steps down from the train, travel-worn, searching the crowd. LUCY WESTENRA rushes to her—sweeter and lovelier than ever, colour high in her cheeks, white summer frock bright against the smoke.

They embrace hard.

LUCY WESTENRA
Mina! At last!

MINA MURRAY
Lucy—oh, my dear—

A hired carriage waits. They climb in with Mina's bags. The horses pull away toward the sea.

EXT. THE CRESCENT, WHITBY - DAY

The carriage climbs. Below, the little river Esk runs through a deep green valley that broadens toward the harbour. A great viaduct strides across on high piers. Red-roofed houses of the old town pile one over another like a picture of Nuremberg. Above all, the ruin of Whitby Abbey stands noble and immense against the sky.

Mina drinks it in, hand tight in Lucy's.

INT. WESTENRA LODGINGS, THE CRESCENT - DAY

A bright sitting-room with sea-light at the windows. MRS. WESTENRA greets Mina warmly, then gathers gloves and card-case.

MRS. WESTENRA
Duty calls only, my dears. We shan't be long. Lucy, keep Mina from working herself to death the first hour.

LUCY WESTENRA
I shall try, Mamma.

Mrs. Westenra goes. Lucy squeezes Mina's arm, already pulling her toward the door again.

LUCY WESTENRA
Come up to the churchyard before the light goes. You must see it.

EXT. WHITBY CHURCHYARD - DAY

High over the town: a big graveyard full of tombstones, walks and seats, the harbour and bay spread below to the headland of Kettleness. Part of the bank has fallen away; stonework of old graves juts out over the sandy path far beneath. Wind off the sea. Bells somewhere distant.

MINA MURRAY sits on a seat with her journal on her knee, writing. Three old men occupy the next bench. The eldest—MR. SWALES, face gnarled and twisted like tree-bark, nearly a hundred—watches the water.

Mina glances up as he shuffles nearer.

MINA MURRAY
They have a legend here—that when a ship is lost, bells are heard out at sea. And a white lady in one of the abbey windows—

MR. SWALES
I wouldn't fash masel' about them, miss. Them things be all wore out. Mind, I don't say that they never was, but I do say that they wasn't in my time. They be all very well for comers and trippers, an' the like, but not for a nice young lady like you. Them feet-folks from York and Leeds that be always eatin' cured herrin's an' drinkin' tea an' lookin' out to buy cheap jet would creed aught. I wonder masel' who'd be bothered tellin' lies to them—even the newspapers, which is full of fool-talk.

MINA MURRAY
(smiling, undaunted)
Would you mind telling me something about the whale-fishing in the old days?

Mr. Swales settles, pleased—then the church clock strikes six. He labours up with his stick.

MR. SWALES
I must gang ageeanwards home now, miss. My grand-daughter doesn't like to be kept waitin' when the tea is ready, for it takes me time to crammle aboon the grees, for there be a many of 'em; an', miss, I lack belly-timber sairly by the clock.

He hobbles toward the long curving stone steps that wind down to the town—hundreds of them, slope so gentle a horse could walk them. Mina watches him go, then closes her book.

EXT. WHITBY CHURCHYARD - DAY

Days later. Bright sun. LUCY WESTENRA in white lawn frock, beautiful colour in her face, sits with MINA MURRAY. MR. SWALES and his two cronies lose no time joining them. The old men soften toward Lucy at once; even Swales does not contradict her—he turns the full force of his talk on Mina instead.

MINA MURRAY
And the legends, Mr. Swales—the bans and warnings—

MR. SWALES
It be all fool-talk, lock, stock, and barrel; that's what it be, an' nowt else. These bans an' wafts an' boh-ghosts an' barguests an' bogles an' all anent them is only fit to set bairns an' dizzy women a-belderin'. They be nowt but air-blebs. They, an' all grims an' signs an' warnin's, be all invented by parsons an' illsome beuk-bodies an' railway touters to skeer an' scunner hafflin's, an' to get folks to do somethin' that they don't other incline to. It makes me ireful to think o' them. Why, it's them that, not content with printin' lies on paper an' preachin' them out of pulpits, does want to be cuttin' them on the tombstones. Look here all around you in what airt ye will; all them steans, holdin' up their heads as well as they can out of their pride, is acant—simply tumblin' down with the weight o' the lies wrote on them, "Here lies the body" or "Sacred to the memory" wrote on all of them, an' yet in nigh half of them there bean't no bodies at all; an' the memories of them bean't cared a pinch of snuff about, much less sacred. Lies all of them, nothin' but lies of one kind or another!

He looks round for his cronies' approval. They nod. Mina feeds the fire.

MINA MURRAY
Oh, Mr. Swales, you can't be serious. Surely these tombstones are not all wrong?

MR. SWALES
Yabblins! There may be a poorish few not wrong, savin' where they make out the people too good. The whole thing be only lies. Now look you here; you come here a stranger, an' you see this kirk-garth. And you consate that all these steans be aboon folk that be happed here, snod an' snog? Then that be just where the lie comes in. Why, there be scores of these lay-beds that be toom as old Dun's 'bacca-box on Friday night.

He nudges a companion; they cackle.

MR. SWALES
Look at that one, the aftest abaft the bier-bank: read it!

Mina rises, crosses, and reads aloud from a leaning stone:

MINA MURRAY
"Edward Spencelagh, master mariner, murdered by pirates off the coast of Andres, April, 1854, aet. 30."

MR. SWALES
Who brought him home, I wonder, to hap him here? Murdered off the coast of Andres! an' you consated his body lay under! Why, I could name ye a dozen whose bones lie in the Greenland seas above—or where the currents may have drifted them. This Braithwaite Lowrey—I knew his father, lost in the Lively off Greenland in '20; or Andrew Woodhouse, drowned in the same seas in 1777; or John Paxton, drowned off Cape Farewell a year later; or old John Rawlings, whose grandfather sailed with me, drowned in the Gulf of Finland in '50. Do ye think that all these men will have to make a rush to Whitby when the trumpet sounds? I have me antherums aboot it!

MINA MURRAY
But surely you are not quite correct, for you start on the assumption that all the poor people, or their spirits, will have to take their tombstones with them on the Day of Judgment. Do you think that will be really necessary?

MR. SWALES
Well, what else be they tombstones for? Answer me that, miss!

MINA MURRAY
To please their relatives, I suppose.

MR. SWALES
To please their relatives, you suppose!

Intense scorn. He stabs his stick toward a slab under their seat, close to the cliff edge.

MR. SWALES
Read the lies on that thruff-stean.

Lucy leans over; the letters face her.

LUCY WESTENRA
"Sacred to the memory of George Canon, who died, in the hope of a glorious resurrection, on July, 29, 1873, falling from the rocks at Kettleness. This tomb was erected by his sorrowing mother to her dearly beloved son. 'He was the only son of his mother, and she was a widow.'"

She looks up, grave.

LUCY WESTENRA
Really, Mr. Swales, I don't see anything very funny in that!

MR. SWALES
Ye don't see aught funny! Ha! ha! But that's because ye don't gawm the sorrowin' mother was a hell-cat that hated him because he was acrewk'd—a regular lamiter he was—an' he hated her so that he committed suicide in order that she mightn't get an insurance she put on his life. He blew nigh the top of his head off with an old musket that they had for scarin' the crows with. 'Twarn't for crows then, for it brought the crows to him!

Lucy turns pale. Mina steers the talk gently away. The old men subside. Sea-light softens on the stones.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Mina writes by candle. Lucy sleeps, colour in her cheeks, breathing softly. Of late Lucy has walked in her sleep—an old childhood habit returned.

MINA MURRAY (V.O.)
Lucy is asleep and looks, oh, so sweet. I am so happy tonight because dear Lucy seems better. I should be quite happy if I only knew if Jonathan... God bless and keep him.

Mina closes the diary, locks the door, ties the key to her wrist. Blows out the candle.

EXT. WHITBY CHURCHYARD - DUSK

Sultry August light. Holiday-makers thin along the cliff walk. High in the north-west sky, mares'-tails streak the blue.

COASTGUARD DONOVAN stands with his spy-glass. An OLD FISHERMAN beside him squints seaward, emphatic.

OLD FISHERMAN
She's comin'. Sudden. Mark me.

On the wide sweep of sea to the north and east, a foreign schooner holds all sail, going westwards—foolhardy, idle on the swell.

COASTGUARD DONOVAN
Russian, by the look. She doesn't know her mind a bit.

Painters sketch the sunset: flame, purple, pink, green, violet, gold—and masses of absolute blackness like colossal silhouettes. Before the sun dips below Kettleness, captains on the walk decide their cobbles and mules stay in harbour.

Wind falls away. The schooner's sails flap idle.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
As idle as a painted ship upon a painted ocean.

EXT. WHITBY HARBOUR - NIGHT

Dead calm. Sultry heat. Few lights at sea. Coasting steamers keep well out. On the pier, a band plays a lively French air—thin against the silence. A sheep bleats inland. A dog barks in the town.

Shortly before ten, the air grows oppressive.

A little after midnight: a strange hollow booming from over the sea, faint, high overhead.

Then the tempest breaks.

Waves rise in growing fury, white-crested, roaring, devouring. Spume sweeps the lanthorns on both piers. Wind roars like thunder. Strong men cling to iron stanchions. Officials clear the piers of onlookers.

Masses of sea-fog drift inland—white, wet, ghostly, dank and cold.

Lightning thick and fast. Thunder peals. In the glare: fishing-boats with rags of sail running madly for shelter; white wings of a storm-tossed sea-bird.

On the summit of the East Cliff, officers work a new searchlight. In pauses of the mist it sweeps the sea. A fishing-boat, gunwale under, rushes into harbour by its guidance. A shout of joy from shore—cleaves the gale a moment, then is swept away.

The searchlight finds, some distance out, a schooner with all sails set—the same vessel. Wind has backed east. Between her and the port lies the great flat reef. Watchers shudder.

OLD FISHERMAN
(shouting over wind)
She must fetch up somewhere, if it was only in hell!

Another rush of sea-fog—a grey pall. Only hearing left: roar, crash, boom.

Wind shifts north-east. Fog melts.

Between the piers, leaping wave to wave at headlong speed, the strange schooner sweeps in with all sail set and gains the harbour.

The searchlight follows her.

Lashed to the helm: a CORPSE, head drooping, swinging horribly with each motion. No other form on deck.

Awe on every face.

The schooner does not pause. She rushes across the harbour and pitches onto the sand-and-gravel heap at the south-east corner under the East Cliff—Tate Hill Pier.

Concussion. Spars, ropes, stays strain. Top-hammer crashes down.

The very instant the shore is touched, an IMMENSE DOG springs up on deck from below as if shot by the blow, runs forward, jumps from the bow to the sand, and makes straight for the steep cliff where the churchyard hangs over the laneway—tombstones projecting over fallen cliff—and disappears into darkness beyond the searchlight's focus.

EXT. TATE HILL PIER - NIGHT

No one on the little pier at first. COASTGUARD DONOVAN runs down from the eastern side, first to climb aboard.

Searchlight men scour the entrance, then hold the beam on the derelict.

Donovan runs aft to the wheel, bends to examine—and recoils as under a blow.

Crowds begin to run the long way round by the Drawbridge. A NEWSPAPER CORRESPONDENT arrives ahead of most. Police and coastguard hold the crowd off the ship. By courtesy Donovan lets the correspondent and a small group climb on deck.

At the wheel: the dead seaman, hands tied one over the other to a spoke. Between inner hand and wood, a crucifix; beads around both wrists and wheel, all kept fast by the binding cords. Flesh cut to the bone where cords worked through the buffeting.

SURGEON CAFFYN arrives, examines.

SURGEON CAFFYN
Dead for quite two days.

In the corpse's pocket: a carefully corked bottle, empty save a little roll of paper—the addendum to the log.

COASTGUARD DONOVAN
He must have tied up his own hands. Fastened the knots with his teeth.

They cut the body free with reverence and bear it away toward the mortuary. Storm already abating. Sky begins to redden over the Yorkshire wolds.

EXT. DEMETER DECK - DAY (FLASHBACK — LOG)

Silver sand. Great wooden boxes of earth. CAPTAIN OF THE DEMETER—weathered, steadfast, middle-aged, dark beard, heavy coat—writes in the log as crew work. Five hands, two mates, cook.

CAPTAIN OF THE DEMETER (V.O.)
Varna to Whitby. Written 18 July. Things so strange happening, that I shall keep accurate note henceforth till we land. On 6 July we finished taking in cargo, silver sand and boxes of earth. At noon set sail.

Quick flashes: Bosphorus—Turkish Customs, backsheesh. Dardanelles. Cape Matapan. Crew cross themselves, scared, will not speak out.

EXT. DEMETER DECK - NIGHT (FLASHBACK)

Mate's watch. One hand, PETROFSKY, relieved—does not go to bunk. Dawn: he is missing.

Crew downcast.

CREWMAN OLGAREN
There is something aboard.

INT. DEMETER CABIN - DAY (FLASHBACK)

OLGAREN, awestruck, confides to the Captain.

CREWMAN OLGAREN
A tall, thin man—not like any of the crew—came up the companion-way and went along the deck forward, and disappeared. Hatchways all closed. No one.

EXT. DEMETER DECK - DAY (FLASHBACK)

Captain musters the whole crew. MATE DRAGOMIR—Roumanian, strong, impatient—scowls.

MATE DRAGOMIR
Folly. Yield to such foolish ideas and you demoralise the men. I will keep them out of trouble with a handspike.

Captain lets him take the helm. The rest search stem to stern with lanterns, abreast. Only the big wooden boxes. No odd corners. Men relieved. Mate Dragomir scowls, says nothing.

EXT. DEMETER DECK - NIGHT (FLASHBACK)

Bay of Biscay. Wild weather. Another man gone off watch—disappeared. Panic. Round robin for double watch. Mate Dragomir angry.

Later: four days in a maelstrom. No sleep. Second mate volunteers helm so men may snatch rest.

Morning watch: no one except steersman. Second mate gone. Thorough search—nothing.

Captain and Mate Dragomir arm themselves.

Fog. English Channel. Cannot work sails—run before the wind. Dare not lower. Drifting.

CAPTAIN OF THE DEMETER (V.O.)
We seem to be drifting to some terrible doom.

EXT. DEMETER DECK - NIGHT (FLASHBACK)

Fog thick. Captain wakes to a cry outside his port. Rushes on deck—runs against Mate Dragomir. Man of watch gone. One more.

MATE DRAGOMIR
(past Dover; North Foreland in a lift of fog)
Only God can guide us. And God seems to have deserted us.

EXT. DEMETER DECK - MIDNIGHT (FLASHBACK)

Captain goes to relieve the wheel—finds no one. Wind steady; no yawing. He dares not leave it. Shouts. Mate Dragomir rushes up in flannels, wild-eyed, haggard. Whispers hoarsely, mouth to the Captain's ear:

MATE DRAGOMIR
It is here; I know it, now. On the watch last night I saw It, like a man, tall and thin, and ghastly pale. It was in the bows, looking out. I crept behind It, and gave It my knife—but the knife went through It, empty as the air.

He drives his knife savagely into empty space.

MATE DRAGOMIR
But It is here, and I'll find It. It is in the hold, perhaps in one of those boxes. I'll sluice them out if need be!

He snatches a lantern and plunges below. A fearful scream from the hold—then silence.

Captain waits at the wheel, alone. Mate Dragomir does not return. At last a splash alongside—something heavy gone into the sea.

CAPTAIN OF THE DEMETER (V.O.)
I shall tie my hands to the wheel when my strength begins to fail, and along with them I shall tie that which He—It!—dare not touch. Thus, and thus only, shall we land.

He binds the crucifix between his wrists and the spoke. The schooner drives on through fog and storm toward Whitby—cargo of earth unbroken in the hold.

EXT. WHITBY CHURCHYARD - DAY

After the storm. Mina and Lucy on their seat. Below, the wrecked schooner Demeter lies under the East Cliff. Crowds stare. The immense dog is not found.

MR. SWALES sits heavily, quieter than his wont. He looks long at the sea.

MR. SWALES
I have seen a deal o' life in my time, miss—an' I tell ye true, I felt the air grow cold when yon ship came in. Mind yersel', an' the pretty one beside ye.

He rises with effort and goes down the steps for the last time we will see him whole.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Mina writes by candle. Lucy sleeps, colour in her cheeks, breathing softly.

MINA MURRAY (V.O.)
Oh, but I am tired. We had a lovely walk. Cows near the lighthouse frightened the wits out of us and wiped the slate clean. Capital severe tea at Robin Hood's Bay. Lucy is asleep and looks, oh, so sweet. I am so happy tonight because dear Lucy seems better. I should be quite happy if I only knew if Jonathan... God bless and keep him.

Mina closes the diary, locks the door, ties the key to her wrist. Blows out the candle.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Clock somewhere strikes. Mina sits bolt upright, horrible sense of fear, emptiness.

The room dark. She steals across, feels Lucy's bed—empty.

She lights a match. Door shut but not locked. Dressing-gown and dress both in place.

MINA MURRAY
Thank God. She cannot be far. Only in her nightdress.

Mina throws on clothes, snatches a big heavy shawl, runs out.

INT. WESTENRA HOUSE - HALL - NIGHT

Hall door open—the catch has not caught. Mina runs into the night.

EXT. THE CRESCENT / NORTH TERRACE - NIGHT

Full moon, heavy black driving clouds. Clock strikes one. Not a soul in sight.

Mina runs along the terrace to the edge of the West Cliff above the pier. Looks across the harbour to the East Cliff.

Cloud shadow obscures St. Mary's Church. Then the edge of a narrow band of light sharp as a sword-cut moves along. Abbey ruins. Churchyard.

There—on their favourite seat—the silver light of the moon strikes a half-reclining figure, snowy white.

Something dark stands behind the seat, bends over the white figure.

Mina does not wait. She flies down the steep steps to the pier, along by the fish-market, over the bridge, up the endless steps to the abbey. Knees tremble. Breath laboured. Feet weighted with lead.

EXT. WHITBY CHURCHYARD - NIGHT

Almost at the top Mina sees the seat and the white figure. Something long and black bends over it.

MINA MURRAY
Lucy! Lucy!

Something raises a head—white face, red gleaming eyes.

Mina runs to the churchyard entrance. Church between her and the seat—she loses sight. When she comes in view again the cloud has passed. Moonlight brilliant.

Lucy half-reclining, head over the back of the seat. Quite alone. No sign of any living thing.

Mina bends over her. Lucy still asleep. Lips parted, breathing in long heavy gasps. In sleep she puts up her hand and pulls the collar of her nightdress close round her throat. A little shudder.

Mina flings the warm shawl over her, draws the edges tight, fastens it at the throat with a big safety-pin. Puts her own shoes on Lucy's feet. Gently wakes her.

Lucy opens her eyes. Does not seem surprised. Trembles a little, clings to Mina. Rises with the obedience of a child.

They pass along. Gravel hurts Mina's bare feet. At a puddle outside she daubs her feet with mud.

EXT. WHITBY STREETS - NIGHT

They hide in a doorway as a not-quite-sober man passes. Heartbeats loud. Home without meeting another soul.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

They wash their feet, say a prayer of thankfulness. Mina tucks Lucy into bed.

LUCY WESTENRA
Promise me. Not a word to any one. Not even Mother.

Mina hesitates, then nods. Locks the door. Key tied to her wrist. Dawn reflex high and far over the sea.

MINA MURRAY (V.O.)
Lucy is sleeping soundly.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - DAY

Noon. Lucy slept without stirring. Looks better than for weeks.

Mina examines the throat—two little red points like pin-pricks. On the band of the nightdress a drop of blood.

MINA MURRAY
I must have been clumsy with the safety-pin.

LUCY WESTENRA
(laughs, pets her)
I did not even feel it.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Key on Mina's wrist. Twice Lucy tries the door in her sleep, impatient, goes back under protest.

Dawn. Birds chirping. Lucy snuggles beside Mina, full of Arthur. Mina speaks of Jonathan. Lucy comforts her.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Mina wakes. Lucy sitting up in bed, still asleep, pointing to the window.

Mina pulls aside the blind. Brilliant moonlight. Between her and the moon a great bat whirls in circles, comes close, flits away across the harbour toward the abbey.

Lucy has lain down again, sleeping peacefully.

EXT. EAST CLIFF / WHITBY CHURCHYARD - DAY

Mina and Lucy on their seat. Reading, writing. Hard to get Lucy away.

Sunset. Red light bathes the old abbey. Lucy murmurs as if to herself:

LUCY WESTENRA
His red eyes again! They are just the same.

She looks half-dreamy. Mina follows her gaze—dark figure on their seat. For an instant great eyes like burning flames. Then only the red sunlight on the windows of St. Mary's behind.

MINA MURRAY
See—the light on the glass.

Lucy starts, becomes herself, looks sad. They go home. Lucy has a headache, early to bed.

EXT. THE CRESCENT - NIGHT

Bright moonlight. Mina returning from a stroll, thinking of Jonathan. Glances up at their window.

Lucy's head leaning out. Mina waves her handkerchief. No movement.

Moonlight creeps round the angle. Lucy's head against the window-sill, eyes shut—fast asleep. By her, seated on the sill, something like a good-sized bird.

Mina runs upstairs.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Lucy moving back to bed, fast asleep, breathing heavily, hand to her throat. Mina does not wake her. Tucks her up. Door locked, window fastened.

Lucy pale, drawn, haggard under the eyes.

INT. WESTENRA HOUSE - BREAKFAST ROOM - DAY

Happy surprise. Arthur's father better—wants the marriage soon. Lucy full of quiet joy.

Later, alone, MRS. WESTENRA (elderly, fragile, kind face, heart-weak) confides to Mina.

MRS. WESTENRA
I have got my death-warrant. The doctor says within a few months. A sudden shock would kill me. You must not tell Lucy.

Mina promises. They were wise to keep the sleep-walking night from her.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Days pass. Lucy growing weaker, languid. Roses fading. At night gasping for air. Walks the room, sits at the open window.

Mina finds her leaning out, in a faint. Restores her. Lucy weak as water, cries silently between struggles for breath. Shakes her head when asked how she came to the window.

Mina looks at the throat—tiny wounds still open, larger, edges faintly white. Little white dots with red centres.

MINA MURRAY (V.O.)
Unless they heal I shall insist on the doctor.

INT. SOLICITOR'S OFFICE, WHITBY - DAY

A clerk seals a letter. Invoice: fifty boxes of earth by Great Northern Railway to Carfax near Purfleet. Keys labelled. Deposit in the ancient chapel marked A. Cheque enclosed.

INT. CARTER PATERSON OFFICE, LONDON - DAY

Acknowledgment. Goods delivered. Keys left in main hall. Overplus returned.

EXT. WHITBY CHURCHYARD - DAY

Mina on the seat. Lucy ever so much better. Roses coming back. Gay spirits.

Lucy taps the stone slab with her heel.

LUCY WESTENRA
My poor little feet didn't make much noise then! I shant run and hide for fear of ghosts, Mina—not with you.

Mina smiles, but her eyes go to the sea road—and to the empty place where letters from Jonathan should have come.

INT. MINA AND LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Mina at the desk. A telegram lies open—from Mr. Hawkins: no word from Jonathan beyond the early notes; anxiety beginning.

MINA MURRAY (V.O.)
No news is not always good news. Oh, Jonathan—if you could only write. If I could only know you safe.

Behind her Lucy sleeps, colour high again in feverish patches. At the open window, for a breath, a shadow passes—tall, thin—then only the curtain stirring in the night wind off the harbour.

Far below, in the dark of the abbey cliff, something waits.

FADE OUT.

THE END
